    <title>Belkin recalls its BoostCharge Pro power bank due to fire risk </title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="The Belkin BoostCharge Pro power bank against a white background with an Apple Watch attached." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/IRvsoHt9fMFwbZgq5PBHmmXlLXI=/1x0:1000x666/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73752138/belkin_recall.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;&lt;em&gt;Belkin is recalling its BoostCharge Pro due to a manufacturing defect that can cause overheating and the risk of fire.&lt;/em&gt; | Image: Belkin&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="QbP5qI"&gt;Belkin is &lt;a href="https://go.redirectingat.com?id=66960X1514734&amp;amp;xs=1&amp;amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.belkin.com%2Fsupport-article%2F%3FarticleNum%3D336820&amp;amp;referrer=theverge.com&amp;amp;sref=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theverge.com%2F2024%2F11%2F27%2F24307644%2Fbelkin-recall-boostcharge-pro-fast-wireless-charger-bpd005-power-bank-apple-watch" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener" target="_blank"&gt;recalling all&lt;/a&gt; of its &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/5/25/23737658/belkin-boostcharge-pro-smartwatch-fast-charging"&gt;BoostCharge Pro Fast Wireless Charger for Apple Watch + Power Bank 10K&lt;/a&gt; and asking owners to stop using them immediately. The company says a manufacturing defect can cause the charger’s “lithium cell component to overheat” in some circumstances, potentially causing a risk of fire.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="OHVasC"&gt;The recalled charger can be identified by looking for its model number, BPD005, printed in white text on the back of the charger, behind its Apple Watch charging pad. There have been no injuries reported as a result of the issue, but Belkin says that consumers should immediately stop using the charger, disconnect it from power sources and other devices, and place the BoostCharge Pro in a “safe, dry location away from anything...&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
