    <title>A Chinese ship is suspected of sabotaging undersea cables</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="Photo illustration of a lifesaver on a pixelated ocean." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/1fBjvtpAJ2-YFUzPkO32yLh0hI4=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73751589/STK485_STK414_AI_SAFETY_D.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Image: Cath Virginia / The Verge, Getty Images&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="yxFE9v"&gt;A Chinese commercial ship is suspected of deliberately dragging its anchor to cut &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/c/24070570/internet-cables-undersea-deep-repair-ships"&gt;undersea  cables that connect countries&lt;/a&gt; over the internet, &lt;a href="https://www.wsj.com/world/europe/chinese-ship-suspected-of-deliberately-dragging-anchor-for-100-miles-to-cut-baltic-cables-395f65d1?mod=hp_lead_pos4"&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Wall Street Journal &lt;/em&gt;reports&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="N0sgvl"&gt;International investigators reportedly believe the crew aboard Yi Peng 3, a bulk carrier full of Russian fertilizer, dragged its anchor for more than 100 miles across the Baltic seabed, damaging the cables that run across it. &lt;a href="https://www.wsj.com/world/europe/russia-suspected-as-baltic-undersea-cables-cut-in-apparent-sabotage-801cb392?mod=article_inline"&gt;Two different internet links&lt;/a&gt; — one between Sweden’s Gotland Island and Lithuania, and another between Finland and Germany — stopped working earlier this month, prompting the investigation by authorities from all four countries and other nations, according to the &lt;em&gt;Journal&lt;/em&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;
